Problem Statement: 
Implement Min Stack
Design a stack that supports push, pop, top, and retrieving the minimum element in constant time.

Implement the MinStack class:

MinStack() initializes the stack object.
void push(int val) pushes the element val onto the stack.
void pop() removes the element on the top of the stack.
int top() gets the top element of the stack.
int getMin() retrieves the minimum element in the stack.
You must implement a solution with O(1) time complexity for each function.
Intuition
A normal stack supports push, pop, and top, but not efficient retrieval of the minimum element.
If we try to find the minimum by scanning the stack every time, it would cost O(n) per query — too slow.

To achieve O(1) getMin(), we maintain a second stack (st2) that tracks the minimum value at every stage of the stack.
So, for each element in the main stack, there’s a corresponding element in st2 that represents the smallest value up to that point.

Approach

We use two stacks:
st1: stores all pushed elements (normal stack behavior).
st2: stores the current minimum value at each level.

Operations:

push(val)
Push val into st1.

For st2:
If empty → push val.

Otherwise → push min(val, st2.top()).
(This ensures the top of st2 always holds the current minimum.)

pop(): Pop from both st1 and st2 (so they stay synchronized).

top(): Return the top element of st1.

getMin(): Return the top element of st2, which always represents the minimum of the current stack.

| Operation  | Time |
| ---------- | ---- |
| `push()`   | O(1) |
| `pop()`    | O(1) |
| `top()`    | O(1) |
| `getMin()` | O(1) |

| Structure | Space |
| --------- | ----- |
| `st1`     | O(n)  |
| `st2`     | O(n)  |

class MinStack {
    stack<int> st1;
    stack<int> st2;
public:

    MinStack() {
        
    }
    
    void push(int val) {
        
        st1.push(val);

        if(st2.empty())
            st2.push(val);
        else
            {
                if(st2.top()>val)
                {
                    st2.push(val);
                }
                else
                    st2.push(st2.top());
            }
    }
    
    void pop() {
        st1.pop();
        st2.pop();
    }
    
    int top() {
        return st1.top();
    }
    
    int getMin() {
        return st2.top();
    }
};

/**
 * Your MinStack object will be instantiated and called as such:
 * MinStack* obj = new MinStack();
 * obj->push(val);
 * obj->pop();
 * int param_3 = obj->top();
 * int param_4 = obj->getMin();
 */
